ot exercise the actual ranking logic; Integration is the minimum level.","test_description":"Insert a set of 10+ vectors with known, varied similarity scores to a real or local vector DB instance (e.g., pgvector, Weaviate). Query with a test vector, capture returned results with their similarity scores, and assert that scores are strictly in descending order. Repeat with different query vectors and result set sizes to cover ranking under different conditions.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.8,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The LLM re-ranking step changes the order of at least some results compared to the raw similarity ranking when the query has nuanced intent","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Mocking the LLM to always return a different order passes the test while the real LLM might produce nearly identical rankings to raw similarity, failing to capture nuanced intent. LLM outputs are non-deterministic and context-dependent—the same query may produce slightly different rankings on successive calls. Only the real LLM can validate whether it actually reorders results based on semantic understanding of nuanced intent (e.g., distinguishing 'AI books by computer scientists' from 'AI books by philosophers'). Calling the real model multiple times is required to catch ineffective re-ranking.","test_description":"For a query with known nuanced intent (e.g., 'machine learning papers on interpretability, not general surveys'), retrieve top-5 results from similarity search alone. Call the real LLM re-ranker (e.g., Claude, GPT-4) with the top-5 and original query. Run this end-to-end test 10+ times and verify that the re-ranked order differs from similarity order in at least 70% of runs. Capture the re-ranked lists to inspect for semantic improvements in result order.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.75,"Workflow"